'''Hinduism in Scotland''' is all aspects of the [[Hindu]] religion in [[Scotland]]. The bulk of Scottish Hindus settled there in the second half of the 20th century. At the time of the 2001 UK Census, 5,600 people identified as Hindu, which equated to 0.1% of the Scottish population and was slightly above the number of Hindus in [[Hinduism in Wales|Wales.]]<ref>[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Publications/2005/02/20757/53570 ANALYSIS OF RELIGION IN THE 2001 CENSUS: Summary Report] www.scotland.gov.uk, accessed 3 Dec 2009</ref> In the 2011 UK Census, the number of Hindus in Scotland almost tripled to over 16,000 adherents.<ref>http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/testimony/hinduism/index.asp</ref> {| class="wikitable" |- ! '''Year''' ! '''Percent''' ! '''Increase''' |- | '''2001''' | '''0.11%''' | '''-''' |- | '''2011''' | '''0.31%''' | style="background: lightgreen" | '''+0.20%''' |}
==Origins== Most Scottish Hindus are of [[India]]n origin, or at least from neighbouring countries, such as [[Sri Lanka]], [[Pakistan]], [[Nepal]] and [[Bangladesh]]. Many of these came after [[Idi Amin]]'s expulsion from [[Uganda]] in the 1970s, and some also came from [[South Africa]]. There are also a few of [[Indonesia]]n and [[Afghanistan|Afghan]] origin.
Many of these in turn are from the [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]] region of India. Common languages amongst them, other than [[English language|English]] include [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]], [[Hindi]], [[Urdu]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] and [[Nepali language|Nepali]].
==Temples== There are several Hindu temples across the country. A temple in the West End of [[Glasgow]], opened in 2006.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/5194412.stm New Hindu temple opens in Glasgow] BBC News, 19 July 2006</ref> However, it was severely damaged by a fire in May 2010.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/10193284.stm Fire severely damages Hindu temple in Glasgow] news.bbc.co.uk, 30 May 2010</ref> The [[International Society for Krishna Consciousness|ISKCON]] aka "Hare Krishna" also operates out of [[Lesmahagow]] in [[South Lanarkshire]]. There are also temples in [[Edinburgh]] and [[Dundee]] with plans announced in 2008 for a temple in [[Aberdeen]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/north_east/7629100.stm Hindu temple planned for Aberdeen] BBC News, 22 September 2008.</ref>
